</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Consistent with the definitions used for the March 2019 awards, TSR performance will be assessed based on the compound annual return
to shareholders over the three year performance period. Straight-line interpolation will apply to performance levels between the TSR values. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In 2020,
for the long-term incentive awards, there will be no changes to the vesting terms associated with the performance-based share awards. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Other
Elements of Compensation </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In addition to the three core elements of compensation (base salary, annual cash incentive and long-term incentives in
the form of time- and performance-based restricted stock), MBIA also provides other forms of indirect compensation which are summarized below. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Perquisites.</I></B> MBIA does not provide any perquisites to current NEOs or any perquisites in connection with any severance or retirement agreements.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Benefits.</I></B> MBIA&#146;s NEOs receive the same benefits as our general employee population. This includes participation in the healthcare
program, whereby MBIA shares in the cost of employee health insurance coverage; supplemental disability insurance; and contributions to defined contribution retirement programs based on a stated percentage of the employee&#146;s compensation.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Retirement Programs.</I></B> As noted above, NEOs receive contributions to defined contribution retirement programs based on a stated percentage
of their respective compensation amounts. Our retirement program includes two qualified defined contribution plans as well as a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> retirement plan. We do not maintain any defined benefit retirement
plans. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>30 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Under the qualified retirement plans, all employees, including our NEOs, receive the same Company contribution
percentages, which include (subject to IRS limitations): </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">a)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">A money-purchase pension plan whereby the Company contributes each year an amount equal to 10% of earned salary and annual bonus and
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">b)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">A 401(k) plan whereby plan participants can contribute up to 25% of earned salary and annual bonus on a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-tax</FONT>
and/or Roth <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">after-tax</FONT> basis, with the Company matching participants&#146; contributions up to 5% of earned salary and annual bonus. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> deferred compensation and excess benefit retirement plan provides participants with benefits that are in excess of those amounts that can be
provided within the qualified plans or that otherwise do not meet IRS requirements. Participant contributions to this plan are tax deferred until the time of distribution. The Company gives executives the benefit of this <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plan because we believe that all eligible employees should receive proportionate contributions to their pension and retirement plans. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">For compensation awarded for the 2019 performance year, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plan participants are eligible to receive Company pension contributions based on aggregate salary and
bonus compensation of up to $2.0&nbsp;million. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Change In Control, Termination and Retirement Arrangements.</I></B> In 2006, the Committee adopted
a Key Employee Employment Protection Plan (the &#147;KEEP Plan&#148;), the purpose of which is to assure the Company of the services of key executives during a change in ownership or control of the Company, and to provide these executives with
financial assurances so they can focus on their responsibilities without distraction and can exercise their judgment without bias due to personal circumstances. Mr.&nbsp;Fallon is covered under the KEEP Plan. The Company does not intend to cover any
other executives under the KEEP Plan in the future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In addition to the KEEP Plan, the Company&#146;s compensation and benefit plans provide certain
compensation payments and benefits due to retirement and under various other termination events, which are described under &#147;Executive compensation tables &#150; Potential payments upon termination or change in control as of December&nbsp;31,
2019.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx841074_105"></A>Additional Information </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>CEO Pay Ratio </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">As is permitted under the SEC rules, to determine our median employee we used 2019 total
cash compensation as our consistently applied compensation measure, which we calculated as the sum of salary paid in 2019 and cash incentive bonus paid for 2019 performance. Excluding our CEO, we examined a total of 92 employees as of the
determination date of December&nbsp;31, 2019 whether employed on a full-time or part-time basis. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">We believe the use of total cash compensation for all
employees is a consistently applied compensation measure. After identifying the median employee based on total cash compensation, we calculated annual total compensation for such employee using the same methodology we use for our named executive
officers as set forth in the 2019 Summary Compensation Table in this proxy statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">For 2019, the annual total compensation of our median employee,
the annual total compensation of our CEO (pursuant to the methodology described above) and the resulting pay ratio are shown in the table below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx841074_12"></A><A NAME="toc841074_12"></A>Compensation and Governance Committee report
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The Compensation and Governance Committee has reviewed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis (&#147;CD&amp;A&#148;) set forth above and has
discussed the disclosures contained therein with key members of the Company&#146;s management team including the Chief Executive Officer. Based on our knowledge of the Company&#146;s compensation program, we believe that the CD&amp;A fairly and
accurately discloses the practices, policies and objectives of the Company with respect to executive compensation for the year 2019. Based upon this review and discussion, we have recommended to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors that the
CD&amp;A as presented to us be included in this proxy statement and in the Company&#146;s Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The amounts shown represent the grant date value of restricted stock awards that were granted to each of the NEOs on March&nbsp;5, 2019. The values
shown are in accordance with Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;) Topic Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;ASC&#148;) 718. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">On March&nbsp;5, 2019, the Board approved the grant date target value of restricted stock awards under the MBIA Inc. 2005 Omnibus Incentive Plan with the target value equal to 175% of our CEO&#146;s and 150% of the
other NEO&#146;s respective base salaries in 2018. The award comprised of a combination of time- and performance-based restricted shares, with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> in the form of time-based restricted stock and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of the award being in the form of performance-based restricted stock as determined by the grant date value. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The actual amount realized by the NEOs, if any, of time-based restricted stock will depend upon the value of our stock on the vesting dates. The actual amount realized by the NEOs, if any, of performance-based
restricted stock will depend upon shares earned based on performance relative to the performance conditions set forth in the award and the value of our stock on the vesting dates. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">For a description of the stock valuations, see Note 15 to our consolidated financial statements included in our Annual Report on Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2019. See the CD&amp;A and the &#147;Grants of plan-based awards in 2019&#148; table for an explanation and further details of the awards. </FONT></P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">1</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The amounts shown represent the 2019 cash performance bonus target opportunity for each of the NEOs, and do not reflect the actual payment of any bonus
to the NEOs for 2019. The actual bonuses paid for 2019 are reflected in the &#147;Summary compensation table for 2019&#148; under column (e). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">2</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The amounts shown represent 2019 cash performance bonus maximum opportunity for each of the NEOs as determined by the achievement of Company objectives
set forth at the beginning of the year and individual performance. The maximum bonus opportunity represents 200% of target. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">3</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">On March&nbsp;5, 2019, the Board approved the grant date target value of restricted stock awards under the MBIA Inc. 2005 Omnibus Incentive Plan with
the target value equal to 175% of our CEO&#146;s and 150% of the other NEO&#146;s respective base salaries in 2018. The award consisted of a combination of time- and performance-based restricted shares, with
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> in the form of time-based restricted stock (described in footnote 4) and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of the award being in the form of performance-based restricted stock
(described below) as determined by the grant date value. The number of time-based shares awarded was the grant date value divided by the closing stock price on the date of grant. The number of performance-based shares awarded was the grant date
value, assuming target performance, divided by the market value per share determined using a binomial lattice model in accordance with accounting guidance for share based awards that contain market performance conditions.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The performance-based share portion of the award was awarded at target. The target performance score is 100% with the
percentage of performance-based shares that can be earned between 0% and 200%. The performance score will be based on absolute TSR over the three-year performance period starting on December&nbsp;31, 2018 and ending on December&nbsp;31, 2021. TSR
will take into account both stock price appreciation and dividends paid by the Company, if applicable. The beginning stock price is the closing share price on December&nbsp;31, 2018. The ending stock price will be the average stock price over the 60
trading days preceding and including the last day of the performance period. The number of performance-based shares earned will be equal to the number of performance-based shares granted multiplied by the performance score. Straight-line
interpolation will apply to performance levels between the TSR values. Earned shares will vest in equal installments on the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date; provided, the NEO is continuously employed on the vesting date and
does not breach the restrictive covenants prior to the applicable vesting date. Post-employment restrictive covenants may include a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-compete</FONT> and/or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT>
covenant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">Notwithstanding the vesting provisions noted above, earned performance shares will become vested at the end of the performance
period upon a change in control or in the event of the NEO&#146;s death or disability. Upon the NEO&#146;s retirement or the company&#146;s termination of the NEO&#146;s employment without cause, performance shares will be earned at the end of the
performance period and shall remain outstanding and vest on the award&#146;s vesting dates, subject to the restrictive covenants. Performance-based shares not earned will be forfeited. See the CD&amp;A for a table showing the performance measure
values relative to percentage scores ranging from <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">0%-200%.</FONT> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">For reference, if the maximum level
of company performance is achieved resulting in 200% of the target being issued, the grant date values of the performance-based shares would be: Mr.&nbsp;Fallon $2,100,000, Mr.&nbsp;McKiernan $1,000,000, Mr.&nbsp;Bergonzi $900,000, Mr.&nbsp;Harris
$700,000, Mr.&nbsp;Young $650,000 and Mr.&nbsp;Avitabile $650,000. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>34 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">4</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">In connection with the March&nbsp;5, 2019 restricted stock awards noted in footnote 3, the time-based shares will vest in equal installments on the
third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the certain vesting conditions as noted in footnote 3. Upon a change in control, the NEO&#146;s death or disability, or the company&#146;s termination of the NEO&#146;s employment
without cause; time-based shares will immediately vest. Upon the NEO&#146;s retirement, shares will remain outstanding, subject to the restrictive covenants as noted in footnote 3, and shall vest on the award&#146;s vesting dates.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2019. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The amounts shown represent time-based restricted stock and are equal to the number of shares awarded multiplied by $9.30 per share, the closing market

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">2</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">The time-based restricted stock shown was granted on March&nbsp;3, 2016 and will vest in equal installments on the fourth and fifth anniversary of the
date of grant; and such shares are subject to continued employment (subject to certain exceptions). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">3</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">On March&nbsp;6, 2017, the Board approved restricted stock awards under the MBIA Inc. 2005 Omnibus Incentive Plan comprised of a combination of time-
and performance-based restricted shares with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> in the form of time-based restricted stock and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of the award being in the form of performance-based
restricted stock as determined by the grant date value. The time-based shares shown will vest in equal installments on each of the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the NEO&#146;s continued employment on the vesting
date (subject to certain exceptions). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">On December&nbsp;31, 2019, Messrs. Fallon and McKiernan forfeited 86,926 and
52,681 shares of performance-based restricted stock, respectively, that were granted as part of the March&nbsp;6, 2017 restricted stock awards. The grant provided for the forfeiture of such restricted stock if the company&#146;s ABV, Leverage and
Stock Price did not exceed the performance threshold for each respective metric. Since threshold performance was not met for all three metrics, the shares were forfeited. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">4</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">On March&nbsp;6, 2018, the Board approved restricted stock awards under the MBIA Inc. 2005 Omnibus Incentive Plan comprised of a combination of time-
and performance-based restricted shares with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> in the form of time-based restricted stock (described below) and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of the award being in the form of
performance-based restricted stock (described in footnote 5) as determined by the grant date value. The time-based shares shown will vest in equal installments on each of the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the
NEO&#146;s continued employment on the vesting date (subject to certain exceptions). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">5</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">In connection with the March&nbsp;6, 2018 restricted stock awards noted in footnote 4, the performance-based restricted stock was granted at target. The
target performance score is 100% with the percentage of performance-based shares that can be earned between 0% and 200%. The performance score will be based on the achievement of TSR over the three-year performance period starting on
December&nbsp;31, 2017 and ending on December&nbsp;31, 2020. TSR will take into account both stock price appreciation and dividends paid by the Company, if applicable. The beginning stock price is the closing share price on December&nbsp;31, 2017.
The ending stock price will be the average stock price over 60 trading days preceding and including the last day of the performance period. The number of performance-based shares earned will be equal to the number of performance-based shares granted
multiplied by the performance score. Earned shares will vest in equal installments on the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the NEO&#146;s continued employment on the vesting date (subject to certain exceptions).
Performance-based shares not earned will be forfeited. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">Based on the Company&#146;s TSR performance being above target
at the end of 2019, under SEC rules the number of performance-based shares shown in column (d)&nbsp;represent estimated payout at maximum levels, resulting in 200% of the target being shown. The market value shown under column (e)&nbsp;reflects the
maximum number of performance-based shares multiplied by $9.30 per share, the closing market value of the shares on December&nbsp;31, 2019. For reference, if these amounts were calculated based on the actual performance level of 114.5% as of
December&nbsp;31, 2019, the number and market value of the performance-based shares would be: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:10px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV ALIGN="right">

and performance-based restricted shares with <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-third</FONT> in the form of time-based restricted stock (described below) and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> of the award being in the form of
performance-based restricted stock (described in footnote 8) as determined by the grant date value. The time-based shares shown will vest in equal installments on each of the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the
NEO&#146;s continued employment on the vesting date (subject to certain exceptions). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">8</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="1">In connection with the March&nbsp;5, 2019 restricted stock awards noted in footnote 7, the performance-based restricted stock was granted at target. The
target performance score is 100% with the percentage of performance-based shares that can be earned between 0% and 200%. The performance score will be based on the achievement of TSR over the three-year performance period starting on
December&nbsp;31, 2018 and ending on December&nbsp;31, 2021. TSR will take into account both stock price appreciation and dividends paid by the Company, if applicable. The beginning stock price is the closing share price on December&nbsp;31, 2018.
The ending stock price will be the average stock price over 60 trading days preceding and including the last day of the performance period. The number of performance-based shares earned will be equal to the number of performance-based shares granted
multiplied by the performance score. Earned shares will vest in equal installments on the third, fourth and fifth anniversary of the grant date, subject to the NEO&#146;s continued employment on the vesting date (subject to certain exceptions).
Performance-based shares not earned will be forfeited. See the CD&amp;A for a table showing the performance measure values relative to percentage scores ranging from <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">0%-200%.</FONT> </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">MBIA maintains a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> defined contribution retirement plan. Under this plan, MBIA contributes amounts
that it is precluded from contributing to the money-purchase pension and 401(k) plans because of Internal Revenue Code limitations. The amounts contributed include both Company and NEO contributions. For compensation awarded for the 2019 performance
year, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plan participants are eligible to receive Company pension contributions based on aggregate salary and bonus compensation of up to $2.0&nbsp;million. The Company contributions shown in the
table above include Company pension contributions made in 2019 for the 2018 performance year. NEOs become fully vested in Company contributions on the fifth year of participation in the plan. The NEO contribution amounts are included in the salary
and performance bonus as reported in the &#147;Summary compensation table for 2019&#148; under columns (c)&nbsp;and (e) respectively. The Company contribution amounts are included in all other compensation as reported in the &#147;Summary
compensation table for 2019&#148; under column (f). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">2</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Assets under this plan are participant-directed and employee account balances and contributions are subject to market-based returns. Plan participants
may self-direct their investments among multiple investment options. The earnings (losses) shown represent the change in market value in 2019, including any dividends and interest earned, which was reduced by any transaction fees incurred during the
year. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx841074_19"></A><A NAME="toc841074_19"></A>Potential payments upon termination or change in control as of
December&nbsp;31, 2019 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s compensation and benefit plans provide certain compensation payments and benefits under various
termination events. The following summaries describe potential compensation and benefits payable to the NEOs upon termination of employment under the following events: (a)&nbsp;involuntary (not for cause) or constructive termination following a
change in control, (b)&nbsp;retirement (if eligible), (c)&nbsp;voluntary termination, (d)&nbsp;involuntary (not for cause) termination without a change in control and (e)&nbsp;death or disability. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In general, employees participating in the compensation and benefit plans are treated similarly with respect to the various termination scenarios. Differences may
apply where NEOs are covered under individual agreements as described below. Following the narrative are tables with estimated dollar values associated with these payments and benefits for each NEO. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>39 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>(a) Involuntary (not for cause) or constructive termination following a change in control.</I></B> On
November&nbsp;8, 2006, the Company adopted the Key Employee Employment Protection Plan (the &#147;KEEP Plan&#148;), which superseded any existing employment protection agreements. Its purpose is to assure the Company of the services of key
executives during a change in control of the Company, and to provide these executives with financial assurances so they can focus on their responsibilities without distraction and can exercise their judgment without bias due to personal
circumstances. The KEEP Plan covers Mr.&nbsp;Fallon as of December&nbsp;31, 2019. The Company does not intend to cover any other executives under the KEEP Plan in the future. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">On February&nbsp;27, 2007, the Company adopted an amendment to the KEEP Plan. A copy of the amended KEEP Plan and a form of an individual agreement has been filed as Exhibit 10.80 and Exhibit 10.81, respectively,
to the Company&#146;s Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filed on March&nbsp;1, 2007. The Company adopted another amendment on February&nbsp;22, 2010 to the KEEP Plan. A copy of this amendment has been filed as Exhibit 10.13 to the
Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filed on March&nbsp;1, 2010. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The KEEP Plan provides that the Company will continue to employ
Mr.&nbsp;Fallon for a period of 24 months from the effective date of the change in control; and his position, title, authority and responsibilities as well as salary, bonus and other elements of compensation and benefits are to be maintained at
levels equal to or commensurate with levels existing prior to the change in control. Compensation payable and benefits under the KEEP Plan are triggered by a change in control of the Company followed by an involuntary termination by the Company (not
for cause) or a voluntary termination for good cause (constructive termination). These terminations are each referred to as a &#147;qualifying termination.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In the event of a qualifying termination during the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">24-month</FONT> effective period, Mr.&nbsp;Fallon will receive a lump sum severance payment equal to two times the sum of his
annual base salary and the average of the annual bonuses paid to him for the prior two years. The severance payment will also include a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> annual bonus for the year of termination equal to the average
of the annual bonuses paid for the prior two years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The KEEP Plan provides that in the event of a qualifying termination, time-based restricted stock
will become fully vested and the vesting of performance shares shall be administered in accordance with the terms of the applicable award agreement. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Under the KEEP Plan, Mr.&nbsp;Fallon will also receive continued health and group life insurance coverage for a period of 24&nbsp;months following the date of the
qualifying termination and a credit to the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> retirement plan in an amount equal to the amount that otherwise would have been contributed on his behalf under the Company&#146;s
money-purchase pension plan had his employment continued for another 24 months. In addition, all unvested retirement account balances will become fully vested. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">To the extent that any payments are subject to an excise tax, a tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payment may be made to Mr.&nbsp;Fallon, subject to the conditions described below. To the extent
a tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payment is required to be made under the KEEP Plan, such payment will be made only if the total payments exceed the IRS excise tax safe harbor limit by at least 10%. If such total payments are
less than 10% over the safe harbor limit, KEEP Plan payments to Mr.&nbsp;Fallon will be reduced to the extent necessary to eliminate any excise tax. As a condition to the receipt of benefits, the KEEP Plan requires that Mr.&nbsp;Fallon agree to be
bound by a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> clause and a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disparagement</FONT> clause. A violation of any of these clauses will
result in a loss of future severance benefits and possible forfeiture to the Company of any severance already paid. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">For Messrs. McKiernan, Bergonzi,
Harris, Young and Avitabile; upon an involuntary termination (not for cause) following a change in control there are no cash payment or benefit obligations. There is immediate vesting of time-based restricted stock and performance-based shares will
vest to the extent that the &#147;performance score&#148; criteria are satisfied. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>(b) Retirement</I></B><I>.</I> On November&nbsp;8, 2006, the
Company adopted voluntary retirement benefits which provide certain benefits to the Company&#146;s employees (including NEOs) upon retirement (the &#147;Retirement Program&#148;). To be eligible for the retirement benefits as described below an NEO
must (i)&nbsp;be at least 55 years old, (ii)&nbsp;have at least five years of service and (iii)&nbsp;give at least a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">six-month</FONT> advance notice of retirement. The Compensation Committee may waive any of the
eligibility conditions or amend any of the provisions of the Retirement Program. Changes have been made to the Retirement Program&#146;s terms since its inception. In 2017, the Company made changes to the treatment of
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-end</FONT> performance bonus and healthcare benefits to remain current with Company policies and practices. Following is a summary of the current compensation and benefits under the Company&#146;s Retirement
Program. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Annual performance bonus.</I> The performance bonus will be determined based on the NEOs target bonus and adjusted for company and
individual performance, and subject to management discretion. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>40 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Unvested Restricted stock.</I> With respect to the restricted stock awards granted in March of 2017, 2018 and
2019, time-based shares shall remain outstanding, subject to post-employment restrictive covenants that may include a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-compete</FONT> and/or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenant, and
will vest on the award&#146;s vesting dates. Performance shares will be earned at the end of the performance period and shall remain outstanding and will vest on the award&#146;s vesting dates, subject to the restrictive covenants as noted above.
For the November 2018 restricted stock award all shares will be forfeited. All other time-based restricted stock will immediately vest upon the retirement date. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Long-term incentive award</I>. The Company will provide a cash payment in consideration of the LTI award that otherwise would have been granted to the NEO in the current or subsequent year, with such payment
prorated based on the number of months of service in the year of retirement and subject to management discretion. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Restrictive covenants.</I> The
vesting of LTI and cash payment in consideration of LTI will require the NEO to consent to a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disparagement</FONT> provision; and at management&#146;s
discretion, a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-compete</FONT> restriction. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Health care benefits.</I> The NEOs can continue medical and dental
benefits under the Company&#146;s health care program until age 65 with the NEO assuming the full premium costs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Retirement plans.</I> Vested account
balances under the 401(k), money-purchase pension and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plans remain available and unvested balances are forfeited. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><I>Accrued and unused vacation.</I> Accrued and unused vacation time as of the retirement date will be paid at retirement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>(c) Voluntary termination.</I></B> Upon the voluntary termination or resignation of an NEO, there are no cash payment obligations and unvested time- and performance-based restricted stock is forfeited. Vested
account balances under the 401(k), money-purchase pension and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plans remain available and unvested balances are forfeited. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>(d) Involuntary (not for cause) termination without change in control.</I></B> Upon an involuntary termination not for cause there are no cash payment obligations. Any cash payment may be paid at the
discretion of the Board. With respect to the annual restricted stock awards granted in March of 2017, 2018 and 2019, there is immediate vesting of time-based restricted stock and performance-based restricted stock will continue to vest beyond the
termination date in accordance with the original vesting terms and to the extent that the &#147;performance score&#148; criteria are satisfied. For the November 2018 restricted stock award all shares will be vested. All other time-based restricted
stock will be forfeited. Vested account balances under the 401(k), money-purchase pension and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-qualified</FONT> plans remain available and unvested balances are forfeited. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>(e) Death or total disability.</I></B> Upon the death or total disability of an NEO, there are no cash payment obligations. There is immediate vesting of
time-based restricted stock and performance-based shares will vest to the extent that the &#147;performance score&#148; criteria are satisfied. All unvested retirement account balances will become fully vested. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Tables showing potential post termination payments.</I></B> The following tables show the potential value of the compensation and benefits that would become
payable as a result of the different termination events described above for each of the NEOs. The values have been estimated as if the termination event occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2019 and assumes the closing market value of the Company&#146;s
shares on that date which was $9.30. The tables do not include amounts the NEOs would normally receive without regard to the circumstances of termination. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Following are notes to explain the values shown in the tables below. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">(1)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Under &#147;Termination following a change in control&#148;, compensation and benefit values reflect the provisions as described under the KEEP Plan for
Mr.&nbsp;Fallon. The amounts include an excise tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> in order to provide him with a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> for his excise tax obligations under IRS regulations, which imposes
an excise tax on certain payments made in connection with a change in control, and any additional tax cost related to the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payment, assuming that a change in control and a termination of employment by
the Company without &#147;cause&#148; occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2019. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:4%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">For the other NEOs, their compensation
values reflect the terms of their respective stock awards. In addition, the values for performance-based and time-based restricted stock reflect the amount the NEO would have been entitled to receive in respect of such equity awards had a change in
control occurred on December&nbsp;31, 2019, whether or not the executive experienced a termination of employment on December&nbsp;31, 2019. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">(2)</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Under &#147;Voluntary termination&#148; or &#147;Retirement&#148;, Messrs. Fallon and Bergonzi are retirement-eligible under the Company&#146;s
Retirement Program as of December&nbsp;31, 2019 and the amounts shown reflect the compensation and benefits as described under retirement. For the other NEOs the amounts reflect a voluntary termination. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>41 </B></FONT></P>

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx841074_20"></A><A NAME="toc841074_20"></A>Compensation plan risk assessment </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Our Compensation Committee has assessed our compensation policies and practices to evaluate whether they create risks that are reasonably likely to have a material
adverse effect on the Company. Based on its assessment, the Compensation Committee concluded that the Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices do not create incentives to take risks that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse
effect on the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In its assessment, the Compensation Committee considered whether the performance measures used to measure and determine Company
performance as well as the attributes of the Company&#146;s compensation policies and practices mitigate incentives to take undue risks while providing adequate incentives to build long-term shareholder value. The Compensation Committee concluded
that the Company has designed its performance evaluation scorecard, and allocated its employees&#146; compensation among base salary, short-term incentives and long-term equity, in such a way as to not encourage excessive risk-taking. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>44 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">includes estimates for services related to 2019 not yet paid </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Audit</I></B> fees were for professional services rendered in connection with the audits of the consolidated financial statements of the Company, statutory and subsidiary audits, consultations concerning
financial accounting and reporting standards and assistance with the review of documents filed with the SEC. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Audit Related</I></B> fees were for
assurance and related services performed for the loss reserve certifications. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Tax</I></B> fees were for professional services rendered in
connection with general tax advice and services. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>All Other </I></B>fees were for professional services rendered in connection with an agreed upon
review. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">One hundred percent of all the above fees for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2019 and 2018 were approved by the Audit Committee. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">PwC did not provide the Company with any information technology services relating to financial systems design or implementation for 2019 or 2018. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Pursuant to its charter, the Audit Committee has responsibility for the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and permitted <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services to be performed for the Company by the independent auditors. The Audit Committee has adopted a policy for the approval of <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services. At the
beginning of the year, the Audit Committee reviews and approves any proposed audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services for the year and the associated costs. The Audit Committee also reviews at its meetings other
audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services proposed to be provided by the independent auditors. The Audit Committee has delegated to the Chair the authority to grant <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approvals,</FONT>
when less than $50,000, if the Chair deems it necessary or appropriate to consider a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> request without a meeting of the full Committee. <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-approvals</FONT> by the
Chair are reviewed with the Audit Committee at its next regularly scheduled meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">In considering the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of proposed audit or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services by the independent auditors, management reviews with the Audit Committee a description of, and the budget for, the
proposed service and the reasons that the independent auditors are being requested to provide the services, including any possible impact on the independence of the independent auditors. Additional Committee approval is required if the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> services exceed the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> budgeted amount for the services. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>45 </B></FONT></P>

<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx841074_25"></A><A NAME="toc841074_25"></A>Certain relationships and related transactions
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">To the best of the Company&#146;s knowledge, other than election to office, no person who has been a Director or Executive Officer of the Company at
any time since the beginning of 2019, no nominees to the Board of Directors nor any associate of the foregoing persons has any substantial interest, direct or indirect, by security holdings or otherwise, in any of the matters to be acted upon at the
2020 Annual Meeting of Shareholders. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Transactions with &#147;related persons&#148; (as defined in Item&nbsp;404(a) of Regulation <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K)</FONT> are monitored by management, the Audit Committee and the Board of Directors, and all Directors and Executive Officers of the Company complete a questionnaire at the beginning of each year, in which they are
asked to disclose family relationships and relationships with other related persons. Before approving a transaction with a related person, the Board of Directors would take into account all relevant factors that it deems appropriate, including
fairness to the Company and the extent of the related person&#146;s interest in the transaction. The policies and procedures surrounding the review, approval or ratification of transactions with related persons are not in writing given that the
Company does not typically enter into such transactions. Nevertheless, such review, approval and ratification of transactions with related persons would be documented in the minutes of the meetings of the Board of Directors. There were no
transactions with related persons since the beginning of the 2019 fiscal year where the policies and procedures described above did not require review, approval or ratification of the transaction or where such policies and procedures were not
followed. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>48 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx841074_26"></A><A NAME="toc841074_26"></A>Proposals for shareholder approval recommended by the
Board </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="3"><B><A NAME="tx841074_27"></A><A NAME="toc841074_27"></A>Proposal 1: Election of Directors </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">All of MBIA&#146;s Directors are elected at each annual shareholders&#146; meeting for a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> term. Shareholders will
elect six Directors at the 2020 Annual Meeting to serve a term expiring at the 2021 Annual Meeting. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Following is information about each nominee,
including biographical data for at least the last five years, and the reasons why each has been nominated for election to the Board. Should one or more of these nominees become unavailable to accept the nomination or election as Director (an event
not now anticipated), all proxies received will be voted for such other persons as the Board may recommend, unless the Board reduces the number of Directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD WIDTH="22%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="1%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="77%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="2" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="2" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="top"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>Diane L. Dewbrey</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Biographical data:</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Ms.&nbsp;Diane&nbsp;L. Dewbrey was elected to the Company&#146;s Board of Directors in November 2018. For five years, until its merger with Consolidated
Communications in 2014, Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey served as an Independent Director and then Chair <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">(2013-14)</FONT> of the Board of Enventis, Inc. Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey earned her BS degree in Mathematics from Xavier University.
She is an NACD Governance Fellow and holds a Professional Director Certification from the American College of Corporate Directors. Prior to serving as a director at Enventis, she held various senior positions at Fifth Third Bancorp, where over an
eighteen year period she became Senior Vice President&nbsp;&amp; Director of Central Operations and a member of the Executive Management Team, and at Foundation Bank, where in her ten years with the company she served as CEO and a Director of the
Foundation Bancorp and Foundation Bank Board. Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey is currently a Director of the YMCA of Greater Seattle where she also serves as Treasurer, member of the Executive Committee, and Chair of the Investment Committee. Age 55</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Reasons for Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey&#146;s nomination:</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey has been nominated to serve as a Director of the Company
due to her extensive experience in leadership positions in the financial services industry. In addition to her board leadership and senior management experience in areas including finance and investments, Ms.&nbsp;Dewbrey has a history of
contributing meaningfully to community organizations.</FONT></P></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" ALIGN="center">

<TD WIDTH="22%"></TD>

<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="2" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD HEIGHT="2" COLSPAN="2" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>William C. Fallon</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Biographical data:</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Fallon was elected as a Director of the Company in May 2017, and appointed as Chief Executive Officer in September&nbsp;15, 2017. Prior to being named
Chief Executive Officer and Director, Mr.&nbsp;Fallon served as President, Chief Operating Officer, and Vice President of the Company and head of the Global Structured Finance Division. Mr.&nbsp;Fallon also serves as President and Chief Executive
Officer of National. From July of 2005 to March&nbsp;1, 2007, Mr.&nbsp;Fallon was Vice President of the Company and head of Corporate and Strategic Planning. Prior to joining the Company in 2005, Mr.&nbsp;Fallon was a partner at McKinsey&nbsp;&amp;
Company and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">co-leader</FONT> of that firm&#146;s Corporate Finance and Strategy Practice. Age&nbsp;60.</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Reasons for Mr.&nbsp;Fallon&#146;s nomination:</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Mr.&nbsp;Fallon has been nominated to serve as a Director of the Company due to his extensive experience with the Company as President and Chief Operating Officer
of the Company and his knowledge of and experience with the Company&#146;s business and operations, his role as CEO of National and his expertise and knowledge of the financial guarantee and financial services industry.</FONT></P></TD></TR>

independence standards set forth in the Board Practices that each Director named below is an Independent Director and that none of the Directors named below have any material relationships with the Company. Such Independent Directors are: Diane L.
Dewbrey, Steven J. Gilbert, Charles R. Rinehart, Theodore Shasta and Richard C. Vaughan. In addition, each of the Directors named in the foregoing sentence qualifies as an &#147;independent director&#148; under the NYSE Corporate Governance Listing

each member of the Compensation Committee meets the enhanced independence requirements of the SEC and the NYSE for members of the Compensation and Governance Committee. </FONT></P>

<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The Board Practices include the following independence standards designed to assist the Board in assessing
Director independence, and can be found on the Company&#146;s website, www.mbia.com, under the &#147;Ethics and Governance&#148; link. The terms &#147;MBIA&#148; and &#147;the corporation&#148; in the following standards refer to MBIA Inc.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#147;The Board shall consist of a significant majority of independent directors. A director will not be considered &#147;Independent&#148; if such
director </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">is a member of management or an employee or has been a member of management or an employee within the last five&nbsp;years; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">has a close family or similar relationship with a member of key management; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">is a lawyer, advisor or consultant to the corporation or its subsidiaries or has a personal service contract with the corporation or any of its subsidiaries;
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">has any other relationship with the corporation or its subsidiaries either personally or through his or her employer which, in the opinion of the Board, would
adversely affect the director&#146;s ability to exercise his or her independent judgment as a director; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">is currently or has been within the last five years an employee of the corporation&#146;s independent auditor; </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">is currently or has been within the last five years an employee of any company whose compensation committee includes an officer of MBIA; and
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">is an immediate family member (i.e., spouse, parent, child, sibling, mother or
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">father-in-law,</FONT></FONT> son or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">daughter-in-law,</FONT></FONT> brother or <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">sister-in-law</FONT></FONT> or anyone (other than a domestic employee) who shares a person&#146;s home) of a person described in either of the two previous categories. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Because the corporation is a major financial institution, outside directors or the companies they are affiliated with will sometimes have a business
relationship with the corporation or its subsidiaries. Directors and companies with which they are affiliated are not given special treatment in these relationships. The Board believes that the existence of a business relationship is not, in and of
itself, sufficient to disqualify a director from being considered an independent director. The materiality of the relationships and the director&#146;s own ability to exercise independent judgment shall be evaluated, and external criteria for
independence, such as those promulgated by the SEC and the NYSE shall be considered, including the enhanced independence requirements of the SEC and the NYSE for members of the Audit Committee and members of the Compensation and Governance
Committee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">To help maintain the independence of the Board, all directors are expected to deal at arm&#146;s length with the corporation
and its subsidiaries and to disclose circumstances material to the director which might be perceived as a conflict of interest. The corporation shall disclose publicly, as required by law, its compliance with the requirement that a majority of its
Board is comprised of independent directors. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:2%"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The Board will make independence determinations on an annual basis prior to approving the
director nominees for inclusion in the corporation&#146;s proxy statement and, if an individual is to be elected to the Board other than at an annual meeting, prior to such election. Each director and nominee for director shall provide the
corporation with full information regarding his or her business and other affiliations for purposes of evaluating the director&#146;s independence.&#148; </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors recommends unanimously that you vote FOR this proposal to elect six Directors. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Vote necessary to elect s</I></B><B><I>ix</I></B><B><I></I></B><B><I> incumbent Directors.</I></B> Directors are elected by a plurality of the votes cast
under applicable law. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Pursuant to the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">By-Laws,</FONT> an incumbent Director who fails to receive a
majority of votes cast &#147;for&#148; his or her election in an uncontested election will be required to tender his or her resignation no later than five business days from the date of the certification of the election results and, no later than 90
days from such certification, the Board will accept such resignation absent compelling reasons. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>52 </B></FONT></P>

</DIV></Center>

<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Brokers do not have discretion to vote on this proposal without your instruction. If you do not instruct your
broker how to vote on this proposal, your broker will deliver a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-vote</FONT> on this proposal. Abstentions from voting on the proposal and broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-votes</FONT> will have no
effect on the outcome of the election or the resignation requirement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx841074_28"></A><A NAME="toc841074_28"></A>Proposal 2: Approval of
compensation paid to NEOs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">As required by the rules of the SEC, you are being asked to vote to support or not support the compensation paid or
awarded to the NEOs as described pursuant to the compensation disclosure rules of the SEC, including under the CD&amp;A and the &#147;Executive compensation tables&#148; sections of this proxy statement. This vote is not intended to address any
specific item of compensation, but rather the overall compensation of our NEOs, as disclosed under the CD&amp;A and &#147;Executive compensation tables&#148; sections of this proxy statement. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">We urge you to review the CD&amp;A in its entirety to assist you in understanding our compensation actions as described therein. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">For the reasons set forth in the CD&amp;A, you are being asked to vote to support or not support the adoption of the following resolution: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">&#147;RESOLVED, that the Company&#146;s shareholders APPROVE, on an advisory basis, the compensation paid to the Company&#146;s NEOs as disclosed pursuant to the compensation disclosure rules of the SEC, including
under the CD&amp;A and &#145;Executive compensation tables&#146; sections of this proxy statement.&#148; </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors and the Company
recommend that the shareholders vote FOR Proposal 2 to express their support for the compensation paid to the Company&#146;s NEOs as disclosed pursuant to the compensation disclosure rules of the SEC, including under the CD&amp;A and &#147;Executive
compensation tables&#148; sections of this proxy statement. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Vote necessary to support NEO compensation.</I></B> The shareholder vote on
Proposal 2 is advisory in nature and therefore will not be binding on the Board. However, the Compensation and Governance Committee will take into account the results of the vote and discussions with individual large shareholders in considering
annual NEO compensation in subsequent periods. Brokers do not have discretion to vote on this proposal without your instruction. If you do not instruct your broker how to vote on this proposal, your broker will deliver a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-vote</FONT> on this proposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx841074_29"></A><A NAME="toc841074_29"></A>Proposal 3: Selection of
independent auditors </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Since its founding in 1986, MBIA has used PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP as its independent auditor. From 1974 to 1986, PwC served
the same role for MBIA&#146;s predecessor organization, the Municipal Bond Insurance Association. During 2019, PwC examined the accounts of the Company and its subsidiaries, reported on the effectiveness of internal controls over financial reporting
and also provided tax advice and other permissible services to the Company. Upon recommendation of the Audit Committee, the Board has appointed PwC as the independent auditors of the Company for 2020, subject to shareholder approval. </FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">We expect that one or more representatives of PwC will be available at the Annual Meeting to make a statement, if desired, and to answer questions from those
shareholders present. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>The Board of Directors recommends unanimously that you vote FOR Proposal&nbsp;3 to ratify the selection of
PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP as independent auditors for the Company. </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Vote necessary to ratify the selection of PwC as auditors.</I></B> The
approval to ratify the selection of PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP as independent auditors for the Company requires that the votes cast by shareholders favoring approval exceed the votes cast opposing approval. Abstentions from voting on the proposal
and broker <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-votes</FONT> will have no effect on the outcome. </FONT></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B>53 </B></FONT></P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx841074_30"></A><A NAME="toc841074_30"></A>Proposal 4: Approval of the Amended and Restated MBIA
Inc. Omnibus Incentive Plan </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2"><B><I>Introduction.</I></B> The Company currently maintains The MBIA Inc. 2005 Omnibus Incentive Plan, as amended (the
&#147;Omnibus Plan&#148;), which was originally effective upon approval by the shareholders of the Company on May&nbsp;5, 2005. The Omnibus Plan has 14,000,000 shares reserved and available for issuance to our employees and employees of our
subsidiaries, and our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-employee</FONT> directors, participating in the Omnibus Plan. As of March&nbsp;10, 2020, there were 624,370 shares of our common stock remaining for issuance under the Omnibus Plan.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">The table below shows, as of March&nbsp;10, 2020, the shares reserved for issuance and shares available for future awards under the Omnibus Plan and the
MBIA Inc. 2005 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-employee</FONT> Director Deferred Compensation Plan (the &#147;Director Plan&#148;), and shares proposed to be added to the Omnibus Plan if the amendment and restatement thereof is approved by our
shareholders pursuant to this Proposal. MBIA does not presently grant stock options and there are no stock options outstanding as of March&nbsp;10, 2020. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:12px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE="" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL" SIZE="2">Shares reserved for issuance of outstanding awards consist of the following: under the Omnibus Plan, a total of 5,715,714 time-based full value shares
